Basic Education Minister Angie Motshekga set up a task team last year to determine whether textbook content in schools is inclusive and whether it promotes unity and diversity. JOHANNESBURG - The Basic Education Department says while its curriculum assessment policy statement clearly outlines what should be taught in schools, some teachers have overstepped boundaries.Minister Angie Motshekga has received a preliminary report into offensive and discriminatory learning material used in schools.She set up a task team last year to determine whether the textbook content is inclusive and whether it promotes unity and diversity.The department says it s against any teaching where individuals or organisations are misrepresented or ridiculed.Spokesperson for the department Elijah Mhlanga says: The imbalances of the past needs to be addressed. This needs to reflect on the material used in schools and in the way teachers use the material. Addressing African National Congress supporters in Sasolburg last week, presidential hopeful Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma accused some schools of teaching pupils that the ANC is corrupt.The department says Motshekga has been looking into the issue for over a year now, adding that a final report into teaching materials is expected at the end of this year.(Edited by Shimoney Regter)